Correlations between known and unknwon fact SOF

Is there a correlation between the SOFs of the known and unknown facts? To do so, we first need to summarize and reformat our dataframe:

prior_agg <- prior_knowledge_analysis %>%
  group_by(userId, prior_knowledge) %>%
  summarize(alpha = mean(alpha)) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = prior_knowledge, values_from = alpha)

The correlation between the SOFs of known and unknown facts is 0.7057049. We can visualize it here

ggplot(prior_agg, aes(x=no, y=yes, col=abs(yes-no))) +
  geom_smooth(method  ="lm") +
  geom_point(size=4, alpha=1) +
  geom_text_repel(aes(label=userId)) +
  scale_color_viridis(option="mako", end = 0.8) +
  xlab("SOF: Previously Unknown") +
  ylab("SOF: Previously Known") +
  ggtitle("SOF by Prior Knwledge") +
  labs(color="|Difference|") +
  annotate(x=0.18, y=0.25,                                                     
           col="red",
           geom="text", 
           label=paste("r =",
                       round(cor(prior_agg$yes, prior_agg$no),
                             2))) +
  theme_minimal()

ggsave("figures/PriorKnowledgeCorrelations.png")

Mixed Linear Model Analysis

And finally, some MLM to get some statistics. We are going to include all possible effects at the subject level, i.,e., both intercept and slope.

base <- lmer(alpha ~ prior_knowledge  + (1|userId) +(0+prior_knowledge|userId), 
             prior_knowledge_analysis)
tab_model(base)
